1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,000
Every time

2
00:00:01,030 --> 00:00:03,420
that February 29 comes by,

3
00:00:03,440 --> 00:00:06,860
someone I love… dies.

4
00:00:07,200 --> 00:00:09,020
February 29, 2008.

5
00:00:09,533 --> 00:00:11,893
My sister and your uncle died at the same time.

6
00:00:12,553 --> 00:00:14,550
I was trying to call my sister right then, too.

7
00:00:15,200 --> 00:00:17,293
If you really, really, are in love with me,

8
00:00:17,580 --> 00:00:18,833
you’ll do this.

9
00:00:19,490 --> 00:00:21,900
Because I really, really, am in love with you.

10
00:00:22,340 --> 00:00:23,560
From now on,

11
00:00:23,600 --> 00:00:24,920
don’t let go of my hands.

12
00:00:25,520 --> 00:00:26,520
Dating.

13
00:00:28,340 --> 00:00:32,846
Day and night must meet.

14
00:00:32,873 --> 00:00:33,873
Why?

15
00:00:34,380 --> 00:00:36,000
Like chopsticks.

16
00:00:36,026 --> 00:00:37,233
They don’t work separately.

17
00:00:37,253 --> 00:00:38,662
We shouldn’t be anywhere near each other.

18
00:00:38,686 --> 00:00:40,080
It’s for everyone’s safety.

19
00:00:40,113 --> 00:00:41,040
Night.

20
00:00:41,060 --> 00:00:43,600
Professor Wiwat was born on February 29.

21
00:00:43,633 --> 00:00:45,020
It was my birthday, too.

22
00:00:45,406 --> 00:00:47,126
I was also absent to celebrate my birthday at home.

23
00:00:47,140 --> 00:00:48,626
With your family?

24
00:00:48,646 --> 00:00:49,426
Of course.

25
00:00:49,440 --> 00:00:55,260
29 FEBRUARY 2004

26
00:01:02,660 --> 00:01:04,973
Guys, I’m getting off work.

27
00:01:06,100 --> 00:01:06,740
Take care of the rest.

28
00:01:06,773 --> 00:01:07,366
Yes, sir.

29
00:01:07,380 --> 00:01:08,540
Safe trip home.

30
00:01:14,140 --> 00:01:15,140
Crap!

31
00:01:15,180 --> 00:01:16,860
Hey, be careful!

32
00:01:17,330 --> 00:01:19,480
I have a child too young for a father like me to die.

33
00:01:19,520 --> 00:01:20,960
Yes, sir. I’m sorry.

34
00:01:20,986 --> 00:01:22,960
Safety is our priority, don’t you know that?

35
00:01:22,993 --> 00:01:23,520
I’m sorry.

36
00:01:23,553 --> 00:01:25,013
They’re so careless…

37
00:01:32,086 --> 00:01:33,886
Every day, I gotta tell them.

38
00:01:33,920 --> 00:01:35,780
Can I even trust them on their own?

39
00:01:36,100 --> 00:01:37,166
I’m in a hurry, damn it.

40
00:01:41,010 --> 00:01:42,346
Watch out!

41
00:02:46,340 --> 00:02:48,393
(Jiraya Kaewpetch)

42
00:02:48,410 --> 00:02:52,126
(Jirat Chayutra)

43
00:02:52,153 --> 00:02:57,890
(Napat Chayutra)

44
00:02:57,913 --> 00:03:02,960
(Jiraporn Chayutra)

45
00:03:28,960 --> 00:03:29,900
(Jiraporn Jittiphat)

46
00:03:29,926 --> 00:03:32,606
(Traikhun Jittiphat)

47
00:03:32,626 --> 00:03:37,893
(Itsari Jittiphat)

48
00:03:37,920 --> 00:03:41,506
(Onanong Thitirat)

49
00:03:41,533 --> 00:03:45,073
(Supasan Thitirat)

50
00:03:59,070 --> 00:04:02,813
(Day)

51
00:04:30,253 --> 00:04:32,534
What makes you think our chances would be worse together?

52
00:04:32,973 --> 00:04:34,970
This is the first year

53
00:04:35,006 --> 00:04:36,646
someone we love survived.

54
00:04:38,940 --> 00:04:40,546
There’s gotta be a reason for that.

55
00:04:41,080 --> 00:04:42,880
If we find out what that reason is,

56
00:04:42,906 --> 00:04:44,880
maybe we can find a way out of this.

57
00:04:46,880 --> 00:04:49,166
So you’re suggesting we brainstorm and collaborate

58
00:04:49,186 --> 00:04:50,593
like a school group project?

59
00:04:51,500 --> 00:04:52,500
Yeah.

60
00:04:52,790 --> 00:04:54,466
If that’s what you wanna call it.

61
00:04:55,140 --> 00:04:56,693
Isn’t it better than doing this alone?

62
00:05:02,033 --> 00:05:04,400
I won’t let anyone else I love end up here again.

63
00:05:05,060 --> 00:05:06,893
I won’t let anyone die because of me again.

64
00:05:07,920 --> 00:05:09,106
As if I’d wanted this.

65
00:05:09,640 --> 00:05:11,186
Then help me out!

66
00:05:11,200 --> 00:05:12,920
What good does your ego do?

67
00:05:13,880 --> 00:05:15,880
Are you seriously going to put up with this?

68
00:05:18,390 --> 00:05:19,390
Look.

69
00:05:20,030 --> 00:05:22,246
We don’t even know what we’re up against.

70
00:05:23,540 --> 00:05:25,673
We don’t even know if they’ll keep surviving

71
00:05:25,700 --> 00:05:27,466
just because they did once.

72
00:05:28,613 --> 00:05:30,610
And together, we can work it out.

73
00:05:31,280 --> 00:05:33,106
What if we increase the risk by sticking together?

74
00:05:33,126 --> 00:05:34,026
What if we don’t?

75
00:05:34,046 --> 00:05:35,086
How can you be sure?

76
00:05:50,780 --> 00:05:52,360
What are you drawing?

77
00:05:55,170 --> 00:05:56,460
Do you remember me?

78
00:05:58,100 --> 00:06:00,626
I was in the car accident with you.

79
00:06:02,400 --> 00:06:05,500
We also just met on campus, you know?

80
00:06:10,980 --> 00:06:13,466
I guess I got the wrong person.

81
00:06:13,640 --> 00:06:14,793
Sorry.

82
00:06:15,240 --> 00:06:17,486
You kinda look like him.

83
00:06:18,100 --> 00:06:21,066
Only that he’s a little more adorable than you are.

84
00:06:28,090 --> 00:06:33,226
Oh, and he loves talking about day and night.

85
00:06:38,320 --> 00:06:39,480
One more thing,

86
00:06:39,506 --> 00:06:42,313
he is Day’s younger brother.

87
00:06:44,230 --> 00:06:45,313
Older.

88
00:06:45,800 --> 00:06:46,760
I’m older.

89
00:06:46,786 --> 00:06:48,333
I’m the older brother.

90
00:06:49,070 --> 00:06:50,526
I see…

91
00:06:51,040 --> 00:06:53,880
Oh, so you’re really him.

92
00:07:01,860 --> 00:07:03,033
I…

93
00:07:03,600 --> 00:07:06,406
I… am an awesome big brother.

94
00:07:06,420 --> 00:07:11,786
I told Day that day and night must meet

95
00:07:11,793 --> 00:07:13,280
to make this work.

96
00:07:13,306 --> 00:07:14,153
Like chopsticks.

97
00:07:14,173 --> 00:07:15,173
I see.

98
00:07:15,560 --> 00:07:17,053
You’re amazing.

99
00:07:18,493 --> 00:07:19,613
I’m Dream.

100
00:07:22,260 --> 00:07:23,260
Ozone.

101
00:07:29,720 --> 00:07:31,866
It’s nice to meet you, Ozone.

102
00:07:33,500 --> 00:07:35,646
Are you here with Day?

103
00:07:35,673 --> 00:07:37,000
I’m also here with Night.

104
00:07:40,590 --> 00:07:41,590
Look.

105
00:07:41,740 --> 00:07:43,486
Whatever you think you know is right

106
00:07:43,873 --> 00:07:45,480
won’t be right in this game.

107
00:07:46,780 --> 00:07:48,160
I had a girlfriend.

108
00:07:49,120 --> 00:07:50,900
I never thought she’d get dragged into this,

109
00:07:51,370 --> 00:07:52,953
because she wasn't a part of my family.

110
00:07:54,270 --> 00:07:55,800
But she died anyway.

111
00:07:56,640 --> 00:07:57,820
Do you need my help?

112
00:07:59,080 --> 00:08:00,633
Can I draw a star over here?

113
00:08:06,853 --> 00:08:08,186
Hey, Ozone.

114
00:08:08,586 --> 00:08:11,226
Do you believe in this Leap Day curse?

115
00:08:16,353 --> 00:08:18,350
Leap Day is real.

116
00:08:18,660 --> 00:08:20,660
Not a matter of belief.

117
00:08:20,906 --> 00:08:22,353
It is real.

118
00:08:24,500 --> 00:08:25,893
It is?

119
00:08:29,380 --> 00:08:31,900
My mother died because of Leap Day.

120
00:08:40,030 --> 00:08:41,440
I have no one left.

121
00:08:43,100 --> 00:08:44,360
I had a dog

122
00:08:44,780 --> 00:08:46,400
and even he died, too.

123
00:08:47,880 --> 00:08:49,826
Every living thing that you love,

124
00:08:49,846 --> 00:08:51,213
that you care about,

125
00:08:51,820 --> 00:08:53,886
all falls under the rules of this damn game.

126
00:08:57,340 --> 00:08:58,340
Yeah.

127
00:08:58,960 --> 00:09:00,146
I know what you mean.

128
00:09:01,540 --> 00:09:03,340
I know how you feel.

129
00:09:04,813 --> 00:09:06,500
I’ve been through the exact same thing.

130
00:09:08,693 --> 00:09:09,746
My mother.

131
00:09:10,630 --> 00:09:11,633
My father.

132
00:09:12,140 --> 00:09:13,380
My sister.

133
00:09:14,250 --> 00:09:16,360
Everyone I loved and cared for

134
00:09:16,393 --> 00:09:18,046
also died because of me.

135
00:09:20,253 --> 00:09:21,713
It’s a curse.

136
00:09:22,570 --> 00:09:24,773
It’s the curse on those born on February 29.

137
00:09:25,353 --> 00:09:26,353
That’s not true.

138
00:09:26,850 --> 00:09:28,433
It only happens to us.

139
00:09:29,870 --> 00:09:32,340
I asked someone else who was born on February 29,

140
00:09:32,980 --> 00:09:34,793
and he’s living a normal life.

141
00:09:34,833 --> 00:09:36,100
He has a family.

142
00:09:36,800 --> 00:09:38,433
It’s just us who are cursed.

143
00:09:38,453 --> 00:09:39,453
That’s why

144
00:09:39,840 --> 00:09:42,026
we’re better off not combining our hapless luck.

145
00:09:43,610 --> 00:09:46,460
How’d you know he’s living a normal life?

146
00:09:47,980 --> 00:09:49,553
Maybe he went through the same fate,

147
00:09:49,573 --> 00:09:51,550
but found a way to live with it!

148
00:09:56,166 --> 00:09:57,550
Dream, we’re leaving.

149
00:10:03,986 --> 00:10:05,220
(Lecture Hall)

150
00:10:05,240 --> 00:10:09,320
The health system is most crucial.

151
00:10:09,340 --> 00:10:12,106
I’ll keep repeating this point

152
00:10:12,130 --> 00:10:15,533
because understanding the health system

153
00:10:15,553 --> 00:10:19,473
will allow us to systematically take care of the patients,

154
00:10:19,493 --> 00:10:24,173
which will further lead to a more efficient management.

155
00:10:25,910 --> 00:10:27,080
Rattikan.

156
00:10:27,106 --> 00:10:28,579
Night.

157
00:10:28,580 --> 00:10:30,220
Rattikan.

158
00:10:32,140 --> 00:10:33,140
Yes?

159
00:10:33,430 --> 00:10:34,960
What is this lecture about?

160
00:10:35,270 --> 00:10:37,840
Oh, it’s the health system.

161
00:10:38,313 --> 00:10:39,873
I’m asking Rattikan.

162
00:10:40,740 --> 00:10:41,880
I’m sorry.

163
00:10:57,600 --> 00:10:58,600
Night.

164
00:10:59,260 --> 00:11:01,426
Should we ask Professor Wiwat again?

165
00:11:02,670 --> 00:11:04,793
If he didn’t tell us anything the first time,

166
00:11:05,190 --> 00:11:07,230
I don’t think he’d tell us anything if we insisted.

167
00:11:07,320 --> 00:11:09,073
If he had been through the same thing,

168
00:11:09,093 --> 00:11:11,880
I’m sure his guards must be high up.

169
00:11:14,540 --> 00:11:18,200
But I think Day has a point.

170
00:11:20,366 --> 00:11:24,133
Maybe we can ask someone who’s close to him?

171
00:11:26,940 --> 00:11:29,466
Oh, Night, I have an idea.

172
00:11:29,500 --> 00:11:32,913
I know an upperclassman who’s the professor’s pet.

173
00:11:32,933 --> 00:11:33,606
Good thing.

174
00:11:33,620 --> 00:11:34,700
I’ll take care of it.

175
00:11:35,380 --> 00:11:36,469
Are you talking about that upperclassman Win?

176
00:11:36,493 --> 00:11:37,160
Yeah.

177
00:11:37,440 --> 00:11:38,020
No.

178
00:11:38,053 --> 00:11:38,913
Don’t talk to him.

179
00:11:38,946 --> 00:11:39,913
I don’t want anything from him.

180
00:11:39,933 --> 00:11:40,966
Come on, Night.

181
00:11:40,980 --> 00:11:43,520
I really think Win can help us.

182
00:11:43,920 --> 00:11:45,200
I’m sure there are other people to ask.

183
00:11:45,220 --> 00:11:45,806
Or what?

184
00:11:45,846 --> 00:11:47,113
Do you fancy talking to him?

185
00:11:49,240 --> 00:11:50,540
No.

186
00:11:50,566 --> 00:11:52,066
Who’d want to talk to him?

187
00:11:52,093 --> 00:11:54,300
I just want to help my boyfriend out.

188
00:12:00,980 --> 00:12:01,980
Fine.

189
00:12:02,410 --> 00:12:05,586
I’ll let you try three times.

190
00:12:07,420 --> 00:12:08,420
Okay?

191
00:12:08,700 --> 00:12:09,700
One more thing.

192
00:12:10,050 --> 00:12:11,386
Just ask your questions.

193
00:12:11,406 --> 00:12:13,553
Don’t go and play detectives.

194
00:12:13,570 --> 00:12:15,406
If he asks you to go somewhere with him, turn him down.

195
00:12:15,420 --> 00:12:15,680
I...

196
00:12:15,706 --> 00:12:18,260
And don’t forget to tell him that you…

197
00:12:19,980 --> 00:12:21,053
have a boyfriend.

198
00:12:23,780 --> 00:12:24,780
Okay.

199
00:12:25,133 --> 00:12:26,133
Roger that.

200
00:12:38,306 --> 00:12:39,306
Here.

201
00:12:49,886 --> 00:12:52,666
(Humans and Planets)

202
00:13:42,570 --> 00:13:43,570
Ozone.

203
00:13:49,760 --> 00:13:50,760
Ozone.

204
00:13:52,520 --> 00:13:53,520
Oh?

205
00:13:53,560 --> 00:13:55,726
I thought you’d help me look up on Leap Day.

206
00:14:13,720 --> 00:14:17,713
(Apollo, the God of sun and light)

207
00:14:24,790 --> 00:14:25,793
Hungry.

208
00:14:26,130 --> 00:14:27,186
I’m hungry.

209
00:14:28,290 --> 00:14:29,353
Okay.

210
00:14:29,820 --> 00:14:32,673
I’ll borrow these books so we can take them home.

211
00:14:32,913 --> 00:14:34,420
Do it fast.

212
00:14:34,446 --> 00:14:36,573
As fast as slipping into a wormhole.

213
00:14:38,986 --> 00:14:40,080
Wait here a minute.

214
00:14:50,040 --> 00:14:51,593
What do you want for dinner?

215
00:14:52,390 --> 00:14:54,020
Grilled pork noodles.

216
00:14:54,370 --> 00:14:55,720
Grilled pork noodles?

217
00:14:55,746 --> 00:14:57,373
I’ve never heard of it before.

218
00:14:58,033 --> 00:14:59,153
Can you make it?

219
00:14:59,910 --> 00:15:00,910
Of course.

220
00:15:16,780 --> 00:15:17,780
Kung?

221
00:15:18,040 --> 00:15:19,040
Over here.

222
00:15:21,600 --> 00:15:22,600
Hello.

223
00:15:22,780 --> 00:15:25,153
I’m not bothering you, am I?

224
00:15:25,166 --> 00:15:26,066
Not at all.

225
00:15:26,080 --> 00:15:27,326
I’m just done with my shift.

226
00:15:27,346 --> 00:15:30,213
I haven’t seen you since the Open House, right?

227
00:15:30,246 --> 00:15:32,493
I got in right when you graduated, after all.

228
00:15:33,280 --> 00:15:33,753
Here.

229
00:15:33,780 --> 00:15:35,306
I got you something.

230
00:15:35,590 --> 00:15:37,260
Thanks.

231
00:15:37,286 --> 00:15:37,733
Well?

232
00:15:37,753 --> 00:15:39,173
What do you need my help with?

233
00:15:42,420 --> 00:15:44,600
I’m trying to cozy up to Professor Wiwat.

234
00:15:44,640 --> 00:15:46,680
My grades aren’t very good

235
00:15:46,700 --> 00:15:49,486
so I just want to know more about him.

236
00:15:49,506 --> 00:15:50,506
That’s it.

237
00:15:50,850 --> 00:15:52,640
That doesn’t sound worth helping.

238
00:15:53,860 --> 00:15:55,613
Dr. Wiwat, huh?

239
00:15:55,640 --> 00:15:59,120
He’s… ingenious.

240
00:15:59,160 --> 00:16:00,800
He likes hardworking people.

241
00:16:00,840 --> 00:16:03,420
The old nurses said

242
00:16:03,446 --> 00:16:05,226
he barely ever called off work.

243
00:16:05,246 --> 00:16:08,300
He wouldn’t take a day off
even on his once-in-every-four-years birthdays.

244
00:16:08,326 --> 00:16:09,420
So much so that…

245
00:16:12,050 --> 00:16:13,050
What is it?

246
00:16:16,240 --> 00:16:18,060
There was this rumor

247
00:16:18,106 --> 00:16:20,893
that Dr. Wiwat messed up a baby delivery.

248
00:16:20,913 --> 00:16:22,566
I don’t know if it’s true,

249
00:16:23,060 --> 00:16:25,380
but people said the patient died.

250
00:16:26,790 --> 00:16:29,980
Dr. Wiwat got a lot of threats after that.

251
00:16:30,013 --> 00:16:32,673
It was during the first years after he messed up.

252
00:16:33,350 --> 00:16:35,706
He always received those letters.

253
00:16:36,180 --> 00:16:40,126
He got criticized and threatened to get exposed.

254
00:16:40,153 --> 00:16:44,220
There was even a letter with his family’s photo on it

255
00:16:44,253 --> 00:16:47,526
covered in animal blood that stank the whole place.

256
00:17:01,320 --> 00:17:02,380
Here.

257
00:17:02,420 --> 00:17:03,873
Dinner is ready.

258
00:17:06,166 --> 00:17:06,613
Look.

259
00:17:07,040 --> 00:17:08,040
What do you think?

260
00:17:10,640 --> 00:17:11,880
Oh, my God.

261
00:17:11,913 --> 00:17:12,913
Here’s your spoon.

262
00:17:14,150 --> 00:17:15,440
Let’s eat, Ozone.

263
00:17:17,160 --> 00:17:18,686
Ozone eats, eats.

264
00:17:20,480 --> 00:17:21,306
Eat lots.

265
00:17:21,333 --> 00:17:22,666
I did my best, you know?

266
00:17:29,880 --> 00:17:31,186
Well, is it good?

267
00:17:31,840 --> 00:17:34,020
It is the best in the universe.

268
00:17:34,690 --> 00:17:35,653
Of course.

269
00:17:35,693 --> 00:17:37,500
I put my whole heart and soul into it.

270
00:18:07,420 --> 00:18:08,480
Ozone!

271
00:18:15,120 --> 00:18:16,466
How the hell did it get in there?

272
00:18:18,040 --> 00:18:18,906
Hold on.

273
00:18:18,920 --> 00:18:19,980
Hang on to me.

274
00:18:20,590 --> 00:18:21,606
Hang on to me.

275
00:18:22,580 --> 00:18:23,986
Ozone, hang in there.

276
00:18:24,006 --> 00:18:25,086
We’ll be there in a minute.

277
00:18:28,040 --> 00:18:28,786
Ozone!

278
00:18:28,800 --> 00:18:29,660
Ozone, stay with me.

279
00:18:29,700 --> 00:18:30,346
Ozone!

280
00:18:30,690 --> 00:18:32,113
Somebody, please help!

281
00:18:42,110 --> 00:18:43,220
What happened?

282
00:18:43,246 --> 00:18:44,573
He chewed on a razor blade.

