376
00:24:14,730 --> 00:24:15,866
Why do you ask?

377
00:24:16,620 --> 00:24:17,860
Wanna have dinner?

378
00:24:18,260 --> 00:24:19,193
This evening?

379
00:24:19,213 --> 00:24:21,413
I have plans with my friends.

380
00:24:21,446 --> 00:24:23,410
How about later?

381
00:24:23,440 --> 00:24:24,620
Later, you said…

382
00:24:25,950 --> 00:24:27,106
How about tomorrow?

383
00:24:28,360 --> 00:24:30,360
Oh, hey, Win.

384
00:24:30,700 --> 00:24:32,920
I have a question.

385
00:24:33,470 --> 00:24:35,793
You’re pretty close with Professor Wiwat, right?

386
00:24:35,820 --> 00:24:38,600
He always talks about you.

387
00:24:38,880 --> 00:24:39,913
He does?

388
00:24:39,940 --> 00:24:40,706
Yes.

389
00:24:40,740 --> 00:24:42,700
Oh, I’m flattered.

390
00:24:42,990 --> 00:24:44,480
Am I close to him?

391
00:24:44,506 --> 00:24:45,553
I guess you could say that.

392
00:24:45,573 --> 00:24:46,786
He’s a good lecturer

393
00:24:46,813 --> 00:24:48,473
and a caring teacher.

394
00:24:48,920 --> 00:24:50,606
I chat with him all the time.

395
00:24:52,730 --> 00:24:56,986
You must know a lot about him, Win.

396
00:24:57,000 --> 00:24:58,660
Can you tell me about him?

397
00:24:58,700 --> 00:25:01,600
Professor Wiwat is just… an old man.

398
00:25:01,620 --> 00:25:03,140
He nitpicks and complains, like usual.

399
00:25:05,090 --> 00:25:06,090
I think…

400
00:25:08,870 --> 00:25:10,406
We should talk about something else.

401
00:25:11,740 --> 00:25:12,753
Let’s talk…

402
00:25:14,230 --> 00:25:15,293
about us.

403
00:25:18,520 --> 00:25:21,853
Well…

404
00:25:22,006 --> 00:25:23,006
Well?

405
00:25:25,410 --> 00:25:27,533
I like Professor Wiwat!

406
00:25:33,190 --> 00:25:34,190
You like him?

407
00:25:34,513 --> 00:25:35,513
As in…

408
00:25:36,650 --> 00:25:37,666
Like “like”?

409
00:25:38,480 --> 00:25:39,480
Yes.

410
00:25:39,600 --> 00:25:41,206
Like “like.”

411
00:25:41,980 --> 00:25:44,806
I’ve felt this way for a while now

412
00:25:44,833 --> 00:25:47,900
so I just want to know what he likes and doesn’t like,

413
00:25:47,933 --> 00:25:50,406
what kind of man he is, and if he’s a good person,

414
00:25:50,426 --> 00:25:51,893
that kind of thing.

415
00:26:03,180 --> 00:26:04,180
Well…

416
00:26:05,580 --> 00:26:07,320
I think I have to tell you the truth.

417
00:26:07,880 --> 00:26:09,880
What do you mean?

418
00:26:11,190 --> 00:26:12,293
Actually,

419
00:26:12,900 --> 00:26:14,420
Professor Wiwat is…

420
00:26:16,073 --> 00:26:18,070
nitpicking and fussy.

421
00:26:18,800 --> 00:26:20,026
More importantly,

422
00:26:20,060 --> 00:26:21,680
he has an old man smell!

423
00:26:22,553 --> 00:26:24,840
He’s not that great, you know?

424
00:26:24,873 --> 00:26:26,553
Why would you say that?

425
00:26:26,580 --> 00:26:28,673
I mean, he seems like a great guy, right?

426
00:26:28,700 --> 00:26:30,920
What’s more, he just seems so cool!

427
00:26:31,320 --> 00:26:32,320
Did you know

428
00:26:32,580 --> 00:26:33,969
that he stopped being an obstetrician

429
00:26:33,993 --> 00:26:36,466
and became a full-time professor and gynecologist

430
00:26:37,453 --> 00:26:38,960
only because he killed someone?

431
00:26:39,000 --> 00:26:40,780
He did?

432
00:26:41,240 --> 00:26:43,420
How did that happen?

433
00:26:43,780 --> 00:26:45,880
My ex is a nurse.

434
00:26:46,280 --> 00:26:48,580
She heard the old nurses talk about this.

435
00:26:48,613 --> 00:26:51,346
It was his birthday that day,

436
00:26:51,373 --> 00:26:54,660
and he wanted to go home early to his family.

437
00:26:54,693 --> 00:26:56,253
He was in a hurry in the delivery room.

438
00:26:56,526 --> 00:26:58,520
Eventually, he messed up,

439
00:26:59,680 --> 00:27:01,480
and killed the mother on the operating table.

440
00:27:02,840 --> 00:27:03,593
What?

441
00:27:03,620 --> 00:27:04,893
What about the baby?

442
00:27:08,090 --> 00:27:09,420
They said it survived,

443
00:27:09,940 --> 00:27:11,420
but not without some issues, I guess.

444
00:27:12,020 --> 00:27:13,566
When it happened,

445
00:27:13,586 --> 00:27:15,106
people didn’t dare talk about it much.

446
00:27:15,140 --> 00:27:18,073
Professor Wiwat was a famous doctor back then,

447
00:27:18,486 --> 00:27:20,566
so the hospital didn’t want to make a fuss about it.

448
00:27:20,886 --> 00:27:23,600
I see.

449
00:27:27,370 --> 00:27:28,420
Babe.

450
00:27:28,820 --> 00:27:29,820
Babe.

451
00:27:30,060 --> 00:27:31,200
Did you have to wait long?

452
00:27:32,280 --> 00:27:33,900
Did I make you wait, babe?

453
00:27:33,933 --> 00:27:36,233
Oh, no. Not at all.

454
00:27:36,260 --> 00:27:38,230
Shall we get going, babe?

455
00:27:39,480 --> 00:27:40,086
Ye—Yes.

456
00:27:40,113 --> 00:27:41,193
- Shall we?
- Let’s go.

457
00:27:41,750 --> 00:27:43,400
See you later, Win.

458
00:27:43,426 --> 00:27:44,626
S–See you.

459
00:27:44,910 --> 00:27:48,553
You still tell guys who hit on you off

460
00:27:48,573 --> 00:27:50,240
by telling them you like the professor?

461
00:27:50,266 --> 00:27:51,306
Look at his face.

462
00:27:51,326 --> 00:27:53,473
He looks as puzzled as a chicken’s butt.

463
00:27:54,660 --> 00:27:57,473
Well, I apologize on my girlfriend’s behalf.

464
00:27:57,506 --> 00:27:59,720
She’s a trouble-maker, always pulling people’s legs.

465
00:27:59,960 --> 00:28:00,693
That was bad of you.

466
00:28:00,713 --> 00:28:01,873
You should apologize to him.

467
00:28:02,430 --> 00:28:03,900
I’m sorry, Win.

468
00:28:03,933 --> 00:28:05,886
S–Sure.

469
00:28:06,410 --> 00:28:09,280
Don’t do it again, alright?

470
00:28:09,313 --> 00:28:11,560
It’s unfortunate enough for him

471
00:28:11,580 --> 00:28:13,846
